,Recommended,252670,8835798,"Posted: 24 January, 2014",all,MashPotato,"Nihilumbra is a puzzle platformer in which you play a scarecrow-like character that is formed from The Void. As you progress, you learn to paint different colours which you can use to manipulate the world and escape from/kill enemies. For example, paint a wall brown and you can stick to it, paint a floor red and things on top of it will be set on fire.  I bought this game because it looked kinda similarish to LIMBO (which I thought was great), but any likeness really ends with the main character being a silhouette.The puzzles in Nihilumbra are generally quite easy (granted I haven't played it in Void Mode yet, which is unlocked after you beat the main game, and looks more difficult), which, depending on your POV, may be a selling point or a negative.  Beyond the level of difficulty, the game is set up to work against frustration, with frequent checkpoints and hints.  The art appears a bit rushed in some areas (some backgrounds are pretty blurry), but is solid enough, and conveys the atmosphere of the game. The Art Gallery, which you unlock as you progress through the game, is a nice feature--I found the development character sketches cool to look at.The main problem I had with this game is the narrative: the heavy-handed narrator talks on nearly every screen, beating you over the head with the meaning behind the game, explaining what to do next, describing things you JUST did, repeating the same things over and over. A game in which you play someone discovering the world should have... well, more of a sense of discovery, rather than someone telling you what's what. At one point the narrator says ""you are not a child anymore. You can do things on your own"" and I was ""YES! Now he'll leave me alone!"", but alas no, he was back on the next screen.If you can ignore the narrator and are looking for a easy puzzler in which you can make steady progress, Nihilumbra is a fine game."
76561197999746670,Recommended,252670,8367281,"Posted: 28 December, 2013",all,DDP Green,"Overall, I neither hated nor loved Nihilumbra.  If there was a ""Meh"" recommendation option, I'd pick that.The first half of the game is enjoyable, which I think most of the reviewers agree on, based on their play times.  The story is interesting and the mechanics are fun and easy to grasp.  8 fairly short levels in each of 5 areas, with a new color/ability found in each area.  There's nothing terribly unique or groundbreaking in the game, but it's 5-10 hours of fun if you just play through the storyline.On the other hand, the void mode -- which is unlocked after completing the storyline -- is aggravating.  I understand that it's meant to be challenging, but most of the challenge comes not from the puzzles or mechanics, but from the interface.  My main complaint with this part of the game is with the ""window"" effect -- instead of a smooth side-scroller, we get a series of screens which are mostly independent of each other, puzzle-wise.  Not a big deal until your screen/window resolution actually impacts where this transition occurs.  Too high a resolution, and critters from the next screen react to your presence.  Too low and you may not see a trap before it's too late.  Not to mention there are a few places where you'll want to sit near the edge of that transition area for at least a few seconds to size-up the next screen (I found 1600x1024 to be fairly good for most levels).With that said, the difficulty also varies wildly, and doesn't present a smooth ramp-up as you progress.  Some late-game levels are easily completable in a few minutes or less, while some mid-game levels requirie multiple retries due to timing/strategy (I'm looking at you, volcano area).If you can pick this up for under $5 and like a side-scrolling platformer, then definitely get it.  Otherwise, there are probably better games that deserve your time."
