,Recommended,252670,8534829,"Posted: 3 January, 2014",all,Bananenmilchshake,"Ugh, I hate this. I wouldn't say this game is recommendable, but at the same time, I can see why people like it. So, just read this review instead of simply looking at the thumbs up-icon to the right.Pros:1. It has a nice soundtrack. It can get repetitive after a while, but it still manages to create the right atmosphere.2. Enjoyable artwork. Of course, that's debatable, but I enjoyed it.3. The general idea of manipulating your environment. It's nothing new, but the abilities themselves are rather cool.Cons:1. The dialogues. Seriously, can't the voice actor just shut up? The acting actually isn't the problem, that's well done. But the dialogue itself is so atrocious and annoying and pretentious. I don't need a comment on everything there's happening. The game would have been _much_ better without any dialogue at all.2. Which brings me to the next point: Too easy. The puzzles are so easy to solve because most of the time you just have to use the one ability you just acquired. Combining abilities happened very seldom and if for some reason you are stuck, the game literally forces the solution upon you through the narrator and the hints. It's a puzzle game, I want to find the solution myself.3. The length. I don't have anything against short games, but the game can be completed within less than two hours. Then of course you can beat in the hardcore mode again, but that's not the solution. They could've added more content, really.4. The controls. The character is... ""wobbly"". It's really difficult to land accurate jumps and even more so, when I have to do the same section all over again, because the last checkpoint was two miles away.5. The tutorials. Okay, seriously. Why do I need those? Not only do you get to know the different abilities, before you can use them, but there's plenty of opportunities to test them out in the actual levels. I don't need a tutorial that basically teaches stuff I already know.So, do I recommend the game? For a discount, yeah, why not? At full price? Rather not, no. I don't know, the game feels a bit too pretentious, like it's trying to jump on the ""platformes with a deep background""-bandwagon we already know from Thomas Was Alone (which was excellent) and LIMBO (which was excellent as well)."
