,Recommended,252670,8761787,"Posted: 18 January, 2014",all,MalikNZZ,"Nihilumbra is both a very interesting and very divided game. It was presented to me as ""Limbo meets Portal,"" but in practice, I found it to be like neither of these things. The unfitting dark creatures roaming about the relatively normal environments felt more like Heart of Darkness, and the emphasis on the ""paint mechanic"" (there are no portals) gives it more similarities to Tag: The Power of Paint. I was also told that the game made figurative waves on the iOS market, but that is a market so inundated with inane and uninteresting nonsense that the comment meant exactly nothing to me, so I went about my playthrough of Nihilumbra determined not to give it a free pass for standing out from mediocrity. So let's get to it.I said that I felt that the game was divided. The gameplay is divided into two distinct modes, the story mode, and the void mode. The latter is unlocked after completing the former. The story mode is what you'd expect; it tells the story. The biggest problem people will have with the story mode is the narrator, or more specifically, the narration design. The decision to have a narrator in a game about nihilism is questionable. I'd think silent, empty text would serve the presentation much better, so that's what I went with when I played it. I don't think the voice is necessarily terrible, but I don't think the presence of a voice in this game is necessarily warranted, either. The narration is also triggered by your position on the different screens within the levels, and if you die and return to a checkpoint, the narration will repeat every time, and this can get grating. Fortunately, for the people who will be too lazy to mute the narration, the story mode is almost too easy.Void mode is the game's answer to that. It's the obligatory, ""you can't spell 'indie' without 'die'"" departure from the almost insultingly easy story mode. This section of the game is of a very much ""Oddworldian"" difficulty. There is plenty of trial and error to go with the more challenging puzzles. You will die in void mode. I've seen void mode criticized a lot, but again, these are (mostly) iPad gamers we're talking about. Fortunately, you are given a reprieve from the narration, but this can be both good and bad. You are introduced to void mode with the promise of closure to the game's somewhat bitter epilogue (What? Did you expect a good ending in a game about nihilism? DID YOU?). While you do technically get that closure, it's accompanied with absolutely no narration or text, so it's a bit of a dull reward for anyone who played through void mode because they liked the story and wanted that elusive happy ending. The only other thing you get (besides the achievements and accompanying bragging rights) is a ""secret language,"" which changes the text of the narration and makes it the complete antithesis of taking itself seriously, so if you thought the story was pretentious garbage, hated it and want some cheap catharsis, you might enjoy replaying story mode for that, but it will just end up leaving a bad taste in everyone else's mouths, especially with the internet memes which have basically already made the ""humor"" rather dated.There is appeal to be had in both the story mode and the void mode, but I think the whole package kind of antagonizes itself. I don't see many people enjoying the whole of the game. Most people will probably heavily prefer one half over the other, and people who prefer the story mode will have to settle with the bitter ending, and people who prefer void mode will have to trudge through the story mode. Whether you decide this game is worth it to you or not will depend on which of those two types of people you decide you are, and whether you feel that you'll only enjoy one half of the game."
76561198047266382,Recommended,252670,15246002,"Posted: 6 April, 2015",all,[GC]SpiritWolf,"I feel that a forewarning before you begin playing is required..When it comes down to it, due to how the game is laid out, it makes it like the narrator through the game is speaking to you, portrayed as your cute blobby character within the game. It's quite harsh and for anyone with a low self esteem, it can really be deterring to play, it was for me at quite a few points, too. Something of which I don't believe was thought through very thoroughly. It however evolves as your character does within each stage of the game. With that been said, let us continue!The only thing I can draw a comparison to is perhaps Limbo, Portal, Oddworld: Abe’s Oddysee, Abyss Odyssey and partially Contrast.Now, starting with a basic breakdown, you are part of the void (basically your replacement to being in a womb) a place of darkness and decay, and are born to be a little shapeless voidling.. You want to explore and be part of something bigger than yourself. Typically you let that take over and begin a journey that pulls you away from the void, however, this does not please the void as one does not simply leave it.You begin by taking a human like shape, to feel as though you fit in the human world easier, while the voice continues to tell you that you are stupidly deluding yourself for trying to think that you could do such a thing. You ignore it and continue on through little puzzles along the way, and the further you go through, the more you learn about yourself and the world around you. The first ability you get is a blue goop, basically an icy slide (hence the little comparison to Portal I was half expecting the next one to be orange), anywho, this aids you to get through the next few levels of puzzles and annoying timing levels however the puzzles themselves are well thought out for the most part, and give you a decent sense of satisfaction and relief when you figure them out. You continue on to discover 5 other colors, all of which provides you something new to help you through each of the changing environments tailored to each color, (blue-ice, green-forest, brown-desert, red-volcanic, yellow-electricity, purple-void).However, the fact that the void is closely following to recapture you means everything in it's path is destroyed. The world your voidling blob has come to love is being destroyed due to them being frivolous, leaving your character feeling responsible.Final summation; in all, it's a really well put together puzzle/platformer. The scenery is gorgeous but can sometimes be a little repetitive. Music fits in amazingly with the atmosphere being slightly abrasive yet quite immersive, puzzles are escalated in difficulty slightly too quickly with it going from casual to incredibly complicated and requiring a need to have mastered all the colors you've been given, and lastly the initially discouraging narrator. All in all though, it's a worthwhile experience to play through and on completion, it gives you even more reply value, having to fix what you've destroyed."
