76561198064019667,Recommended,252670,8426822,"Posted: 30 December, 2013",all,oakwick,"As a big fan of 2D sidescrolling puzzle platformers, Nihilumbra gave me exactly what I wanted while also bringing in a fresh perspective.You play as Born, a creature that was created in the Void, and you are trying to outrun your fate while discovering the new world you are in. You learn to use elements of the world to your advantage, by finding colors and 'painting' (or erasing) those elements onto the world around you. You can make yourself slide, bounce, etc. You can also use those elements to make OTHER things in the world slide, bounce, and so on. This becomes fun pretty fast, and satisfying as well. The satisfaction I used to feel after making something blow up in Oddworld is the same satisfaction I feel when I make a monster slide off a platform or I successfully rebound a bullet off of a few walls to thwart my enemy.Most of the levels can be taken at your own pace, and offer fair, regularly placed checkpoints to assistant you in advancing. There are a few, but still fair, timed levels, where the Void chases you. There are checkpoints during these levels as well, and though I normally hate timed levels in platformers, these are made to be player-friendly.Though there is a lot of dialog from the narrator, it's spoken as you move, so you don't have to stop for it. So far the levels have been increasing slowly in difficulty, allowing the player to adjust as they continue.I think this is a great game for any for any fans of puzzle platformers. It has the feeling of being detailed, unique, and well thought out, though it's easy to toggle through your colors/elements with a click of the mouse, so it's also nice that it's far easier to control than some other games I've come across."
