76561198076176773,Recommended,252670,33110405,Posted: 1 July,all,Alistair L,"Nihilumbra is a wonderful game.I really don't know why I purchased it, other than it being on sale. The atmospheric indie puzzle platfomer seems to be popular on Steam these days, but I'm generally weary of games like this since being disappointed by Trine and LIMBO, two giants of the genre.But, hey, whaddya know, Nihilumbra is a wonderful game.It succeeds massively where both Trine and LIMBO failed for me, by being engaging, atmospheric, and thought-provoking without forgetting to actually be a decent game. The gameplay is original, intuitive, and just very satisfying to partake in. It is perhaps a little easy in Normal Mode, but it makes up for it by being brilliantly devilish in Void Mode (which unlocks once you beat Normal Mode). The control is well-calibrated and manageable (as opposed to the imprecise and sloppy controls of Trine), while the puzzle design is logical and can be reasoned through (as opposed to the trial and error-based puzzles of LIMBO).The story and artistic design are equally wonderful. I was genuinely attached to Born, the sentient Voidstuff who acts as a protagonist, and invested in their fate. The ending was intriguing and uplifiting, and the aesthetic aspects, including backgrounds, enemy design, etc., were interesting and original. The soundtrack is beautiful, particularly the Void chase theme.To summarize: Get Nihilumbra, even if you don't typically gravitate towards the genre it belongs to. It's surprisingly lovely."
