76561198004585919,Recommended,252670,29675852,Posted: 3 February,all,sircrimsonfox,"This follows a long line of puzzle platformers and it really hits the spot. The history of puzzle platformers is a long one and very much is a genre I've always loved. Way back in the 90s there were many. Usually cartoony in form and had stories and plots. Original Prince of PErsia fits this bill but with the Playstation came 3D and very cartoony characters like Crash Bandicoot and Spyro and such. Also in the past shooting has been part of the mix. But the indie wave since about 2010 had taken things back to its 2D sidescrolling roots and added an art to it that was so new and appealingly fresh. The biggest addition to this line was Limbo. A totally beautiful game. A game that was totally the opposite of lots of platform sidescroller shooters from before as it not only featured a helpless protagonist that was relentlessly tortured throughout the game but had an artistic style and statement that just was pure beauty. So goes Nihilumbra. Yes Nihilism. It's not just for Lebowski fans anymore. This is another success in this genre and it really taps into the most fun bits of Portal 2. Remember the goo levels? This game features a lot of things like that. YOu have this character, this blob...this ""nothing"". That escapes ""the void"". And he mimics the form of a scarecrow. I LOVE this choice. Your ragdoll man floats and blows along. He doesn't walk. He kind of floats. And his ""clothes"" are always flopping in the breeze and especially when he lands from jumps. It's so appealing of a character. LIke the best of disney sidekicks. And then you have gruesome bizarre monsters. Think of all the craziest scariest designs from Dr Seuss or Tex Avery. Stuff of nightmares in shape and form because all these things are alive. And there are different ways to avoid and outsmart these creatures. And traverse this world. Okay now....the guy. There is a narrator that comes across like one of those positive self help cassettes. Always telling you your place in this world. Telling you what a failure you are. Telling you how waful your life has been. Telling you you will never win. And then reinvigorating you with his soothing tones what a success you will be, are being, will continue to be. You are special and goshdarnit people like you, Stewart Smalley. I still don't know what to make of this really. The narrator gives you all the instruction for the game. And then visual aids appear in a lot of places to tell you EXACTLY how to solve a puzzle. In fact they don't wait for more than about 2 failures before the game actually tells you how to solve a puzzle. I am not sure if it does that all the time. Maybe just when you are learning a new move? But I see it often. I've conquered the first two worlds thus far. I guess that means levels. And each world seems to offer new types of gameplay and monsters and moves. Very much like Portal 2 did. More moves and thus more puzzles you solve for those moves then puzzles combining those moves and monsters with previous ones to remind you. It does do a bunch of handholding for sure. But I do feel satisfied playing it. It's like relaxing in a hot tub. And when the swirly purple void emcompasses me...and the whole screen. I don't mind. It's beautiful. Well....unless of course well yes I do mind when it is chasing me and I'm trying to plan for moves that haven't come on the screen yet because...the ....screen....is....scrolling....by....so........S....L...O...W...L...Y.... However any frustrating bits so far have been solved with a few tries, trial and error and whatnot. Seeing how you die and then remembering and preparing for that offscreen jump. And it is satisfying changing the ground to grassy bouncy, maybe just a LITTLE less satisfying to shooting goop everywhere with a goopgun. I'm liking it. It's a satisfying PP...and a satisfying experience. I'll let the narrator lull me with his dulcet tones and float away in my scarecrow body. I really love the animation of the characters by the way. And the scenery and weather are just gorgeous. This is also one that goes on sale a lot from it's list price of just 8 dollars so it's a steal when it does. Get it."
,Recommended,252670,24123806,"Posted: 5 July, 2016",all,Furueisho Peicho,"This a weird game but it's also kinda interesting.What bugs me about it is the fact that everything is spelled out. The writing is not of a high enough quality to make it literarily valuable. And the level design suffers from the repetitiveness. The narrator talks as if he was the game designer, shoving every meta concept down your throat. And everything is established way too much. I'd appreciate it if it was a little more subtle.Although the art is very elaborate, some objects seem like they were done by a different person. They do not blend together seamlessly. And some of them are not cohesive in the game world. Like the laser turrets and everything mechanical.The gameplay reminds me a little of Trine and Scribblenauts, because you draw into your surroundings while being in a sidescrolling platformer. So it is actually a puzzle game. Coloring the surfaces is a little like the gels in Portal 2. You have one that makes you bounce, one that makes you fast... but there are a couple more. It's acually not bad.There are a few beginner's traps - stuff you can't possibly foresee and walk right into. Also when you enter a new screen it may happen that you get killed instantly. It's good to have a lot of checkpoints, though. But you will hear the same lines of the narrator repeatedly.The experience would be better when the narrator would have talked in a made-up language or if you heard undefined, mysterious soundeffects together with the onscreen text.The controls are fine and so is the music.It feels veryindybut also as if they were trying a little too hard to reinforce this notion. It was probably made by someone who is not a game designer first."
,Recommended,252670,8446613,"Posted: 30 December, 2013",all,*UaS*Màtri×,"Nihilumbra combines aspects of life lessons and puzzle solving skills with beautiful narration, graphics and music. The storyline is entertaining but also enriching in the sense that it is essentially an explanation of life and what it means to live. In one word, the game is simply: beautiful.10/10"
,Recommended,252670,24529422,"Posted: 25 July, 2016",all,JimDeadlock,"OverviewYou solve the puzzles, deal with various purple monsters and progress by painting parts of the platform with 5 different colours, each of which has its own property: slide, bounce, sticky, burn and electricity. There are 5 areas in the game, each with its own environment and colour scheme. Within each area you can take your time until the last level which is always a speed run where you are chased by the Void (a purple wave covering the whole screen).The graphics are beautiful and the gameplay itself adds to the beauty as you paint the scenery. The devs are clearly proud of their work, and rightly so, as their gallery of rough sketches and gameplay development is gradually unlocked throughout the game.Steam trading cards and achievements are included and it's cross-platform (I'm a Linux user so that's a big plus for me).No performance issues or glitches at all. Very stable and smooth.Early GameNearly all of the negative reviews of this game show less than 4 hours of gameplay, which means they are only reviewing the Story Mode part of the game, of which there are 41 levels that seem endless. The gameplay at this stage is very easy, I would say the first 70% is child level. The whole time you are subjected to an extremely irritating narrator droning on about hopelessness and death and giving clues to the gameplay, as if it wasn't easy enough already. I was sorely tempted to throw in the towel like so many other reviewers but I wanted to get all the achievements so I carried on. I'm so glad I did!Void ModeAs it turned out, this is a 'game of two halves'. Void Mode is properly challenging, one of the best puzzle platformers I've ever played. I'm talking 50+ attempts at some levels involving timing and accuracy, and that's after you've worked out how to solve it in the first place which isn't easy either. The narrator has disappeared by this point too, replaced by a subtle background tune, just what you need for concentration. Many of the solutions took a lot of brainpower but none were impossible if I thought about it for long enough.AftermathAfter beating Void the 'polyglot language' is unlocked. All the menus etc are slang/internet speak. You can play through Story Mode again and this time there are funny comments from the developer and interesting insights into the game concepts. It's strange because after Void Mode it seems to take no time at all to speed through the entire game (this is the same playthrough that seemed to take forever the first time!) If you reach the 'True End' you will find out what the Void represents.Finally, I cleared up half a dozen of the remaining achievements which, having completed Void, were entertaining but not too difficult (but would have seemed impossible without all my previous experience).In retrospect the Story Mode is nothing more than an extended tutorial. If the developers left Void Mode open from the start instead of forcing you to play through the entire Story Mode to unlock it then players who were getting bored of Story would attempt Void and go scurrying back to Story because they would realise they need the practice and that there is a decent game ahead. I'm sure doing this simple thing would prevent most of the negative reviews.Minor ConsFullscreen only, no windowed mode.No controller support, although this may have been left out deliberately. It would be better for moving around but the painting side of it just wouldn't be feasible with a controller, it needs a mouse.64-bit Linux doesn't upload achievements to your profile but there's a workaround - it's Linux, of course there is :)ConclusionThis is excellent value considering the low price vs amount of gameplay. Apart from the initial Story Mode section (which I now understand was a necessary evil), the vast majority of the 32 hours I've spent playing this game have been fun and rewarding. I highly recommend it as long as you have the patience to work through the 2-4 hours at the beginning before you get to the meaty part of the game.Hot tip: use right-click to quickly erase - it's much easier than selecting it and you will need to know this for some of the quick-fire later levels.I bought this game myself but have dedicated the review to the fabulous and generous people at Steamified.This review is part of the Steamified Community Review program. For similar reviews and fantastic giveaways please visithttp://www.steamified.com/."
