76561197985267228,Recommended,252670,11074232,"Posted: 4 July, 2014",all,ScaryDoor,"I'll be honest: after finishing Nihilumbra, I quite disliked it.  It tries to establish a mood with a constant narration, in the style of Bastion.  But the writing is mediocre and the voice acting is boring, so the entire thing comes off as trite and cliche.I was just about to uninstall the game and never think about it again, when I decided on a whim to quickly try out 'Void Mode'.  Void Mode, unlocked once you complete the main game, is a new game + of sorts.  You start over with all powers unlocked, and are tasked with going through the game again.  However, things are much harder.  There are entirely new setpieces, enemies, and mechanics that really force you to think about things.  All voice acting and story elements are removed.  Void Mode is when the game really comes into itself as a puzzle platformer, and I found completing it genuinely satisfying and enjoyable.I'm recommending the game for Void Mode alone.  If you're looking for a good puzzle platformer, rush through the main game and enjoy Void Mode.  If you're looking for a story-driven experience, I suggest you give this one a miss."
