,Not Recommended,252670,16887840,"Posted: 4 July, 2015",all,BorkBork™,"Nihilumbra is a pretty game devoid of any actual substance, which is quite ironic when you think about the message this game is trying to convey. If you're looking for a deeply meaningful and complex puzzle game, look elsewhere. The puzzles in the main game are mindless and unfulfilling, barely branching out from their basic mechanics. In ""void"" mode (Nihil's version of New Game +), the difficulty of the puzzles aren't scaled; the game simply becomes a platformer-hybrid contingent on split-second timing and quick reflexes. Even with the challenges this mode presents, completing stages offer no satisfaction aside from what little can be had with the absence of the narrator.What's left after the gameplay has been stripped away is a watered-down philosophy 101 lesson told by some guy who sounds like he hates his life. The writing is awful; throughout the game, the narrator beats you over the head with how your poor little guy is feeling (spoilers: not good), but instead of creating an emotional rapport with the character, it's just meaningless drivel.Tl;dr: pretty graphics alone don't make a game, and the sophmoric narrator ruins the game."
