,Recommended,252670,28496945,"Posted: 20 December, 2016",all,ThePhantomSafetyPin,"Ah, Nihilumbra, another one of those ""Cute"" games that comments philosophically on the nature of life, the universe, and everything. Yes, a lot of games do this, but I have never been so attached to a character as I have been to Born, so much wanted to see this character grow, and so wanted everything to be okay for the little mite. You really kind of have to put your own spin on the character by nature of what it is, and that's pretty different from most games like this I've seen.The story is that you (Born) are a shadow being from the Void - the Nothingness, that is - and you, curious about the world outside the Void, break free from it into the world of... Something. Quickly, you learn to become and adapt in this environment, changing it, loving it, only for the Void to come after you time and again, trying to reclaim you. The way Born navigates his environs is through elemental magic of a sort, painting elements onto the environs to solve physics puzzles in a way somewhat reminiscent of Okami/Okamiden. Of course, Okami/Okamiden never left me a crying disaster over a shadow creature just trying to make his way in the world, because puppies generally try not to hurt your heart when they make mistakes. The monsters in the game are terrifyingly designed and (yes I know my reviews say this a lot) really do look like something out of a Lovecraft story. Try looking at a Crawlaggar and NOT seeing something that could reasonably pass as a Hound of the Tindalos, I dare you, especially when it comes chasing after you in packs from off-screen...That said, this charming game is not everyone's cup of tea - there is a New Game Plus mode after the end of the normal game, a sort of ""B Adventure"" where you go back through the levels fixing what the Void has destroyed, and it is ABSOLUTELY BRUTALLY HARD. I'm serious, I consider myself a puzzle buff and a fan of rogue-style difficulty, but this is even too much for me. Split-second timing, rather unfair jumps, trial and error, and using elements to deflect bullets into incredibly tough series of enemies - they're all here, often during the chapter-end chases, and they will bend you over a table and go in dry. I am not kidding here, the New Game Plus of this game reaches unprecidented levels of Guide Dang It at points, and that's not even counting the various achievements that aren't related to gameplay itself! I genuinely needed a walkthrough to even make it to the end, and even that was difficult when you look at some of the absolute bull-hocky that this game expects you to do in New Game Plus. To compound that, Born's hitbox sometimes plays oddly with certain enemies - like the Vacuumore - where even being two feet away from the enemy's maw is enough to kill you. This also appears to occur with boxes and spikes on some occasions. I suspect this is a bit of a glitch or oversight, and the game maker did not intend to make the hitbox quite so sensitive, in which case - please fix this, it makes the game quite difficult for the wrong reasons.At the same time, IMHO, the normal game is almost too easy, with obvious solutions to fairly obvious puzzles. Yes, it gets very clever with them - using the bounce power to ricochet bullets, using the sticky power to stick enemies to walls and ceilings (which is freaking hilarious to watch because they flail around), etc. However, generally any time you need speed, you used the slippery power, making electronics work uses the electronic power, etc. Obvious problem + Obvious power = Obvious solution, and I wish that there was more use of mixing of powers to get to a solution as the New Game Plus does. So, between the main game being too easy, and New Game Plus being too hard (but not impossible), couldn't there have been a bit more of a transition between the two? Maybe like, just add more monsters instead of more difficult puzzles, or add more puzzles but not more monsters? Then you could have an easy, medium, and hard mode for those who wanted to play around with the powers and use new and more interesting power combinations to reach their goals, and you could have had the B Adventure be tougher without being so tough it made me tear my hair out in frustration. At the very least, you could have cut down on the number of timing-sensitive puzzles that are near freaking impossible; there's a difference between Nintendo Hard and Frustrating.All in all, I do still like this game, a lot, and find it difficult to hate. The scenery and general idea behind it is gorgeous, I love playing Pseudo-Okami with the powers, and obtaining each power was a true pleasure and very satisfying. Burning things with the fire power is amazingly fun, and the puzzles are pretty clever all things considered. I would recommend this game, but only if you like physics platform-puzzlers with a tough streak in its New Game Plus, because seriously - that second half makes you WORK for its achievements..."
